-- Japan, Taiwan, India, Malaysia, South Korea: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   A n d r e a   W o n g
-- 2010-09-29T23:13:37Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-29/japan-taiwan-india-malaysia-south-korea-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan:  Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  will hold
media briefings at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Ministry of Finance will publish at 7 p.m. in Tokyo its
report on the nation’s intervention in the foreign-exchange
market in September.  The Finance Ministry will announce at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo it
report on Japanese and foreign investment flows for domestic and
overseas securities during the week ended Sept. 24.  The Trade Ministry will release at 8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its
report on retail sales in August. The ministry will publish at
8:50 a.m. in Tokyo its report on industrial production in August.  The Finance Ministry will announce at 10:30 a.m. in Tokyo
the amount of 10-year government debt it plans to sell on Oct. 7.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.92 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.76 per dollar at 8:08 a.m. in Tokyo.  Thailand: Manufacturing production increased 20 percent in
August from a year earlier after a 16.3 percent gain in July, a
central bank report today may show, according to the median
forecast in a Bloomberg survey. The current-account swung to a
surplus of $602 million from a deficit of $1.13 billion the
previous month, the central bank may say today according to a
separate Bloomberg poll.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note maturing March 2021 was
3.10 percent. The baht was at 30.47.  South Korea: Industrial production rose 17 percent in
August from a year earlier after a 15.5 percent gain in July,
according to median estimate of economists in a Bloomberg survey.
Factory output gained 15.5 percent in July.  The yield on the 3.75 percent note due June 2013 was 3.33
percent. The won was at 1,142.10.  Singapore: The central bank will release money supply and
loans growth data for the month of August.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.04 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3174.  Malaysia: The central bank will sell 180 million ringgit
($58.3 million) of 91- and 182-day bills. It will also release
M3 money supply growth data for the month of August.  The yield on the 3.835 percent bond due August 2015 was
3.23 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0853.  India: The Reserve Bank of India will say today the
currency-account deficit narrowed to $12.5 billion in the second
quarter after a $13 billion deficit in the three months through
March.  The yield on the 7.84 percent bond due in May 2020 was 7.85
percent. The rupee was at 44.935.  Taiwan: The island’s central bank will raise the benchmark
interest rate by 12.5 basis point to 1.50 percent today,
according to a Bloomberg survey of economists.  The yield on the 1.125 percent bond maturing in September
2020 was at 1.20 percent, according to Gretai Securities Market.
The Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.38.  To contact the reporter on this story:
